    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="ITemplateEngine usage (existing call sites)" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Delivery/EmailTemplateService.cs">
        EmailTemplateService + WordTemplateService both inject ITemplateEngine and call Render(template, contextDict). Follow this exact pattern in the orchestrator.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="JsonElement → traversable conversion" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/TemplateEngine.cs">
        TemplateEngine.ConvertJsonElement(JsonElement) returns Dictionary/List/primitive — call this on NodeOutput.StructuredData before registering in NodeOutputs (so Handlebars can traverse `{{nodeName.field.subfield}}`).
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Today the orchestrator's `ApplyConfigJsonTemplates` only handles `{{paramName}}` literal substitution from the BFF's parameter dictionary. The deployed `DAILY-BRIEFING-NARRATE` playbook uses `{{json start}}`, `{{tldrResult.summary}}`, `{{channelRegistry.channels}}` — all of which need the existing Handlebars-backed `ITemplateEngine`. Wave 11 task 110 designed the wiring; this task implements it.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="110" status="must-complete-first">Design doc with proposed signatures + lifecycle.</dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>Task 112 (helpers) and 114 (fan-out) build on this task's NodeOutputs surface.</item>
      <item>Task 115 (restore ValidateEntityNames config) requires this task complete so source-correct templates can actually resolve.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Rigor Declaration">
      Output: 🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL · 📋 REASON: bff-api code-impl, modifies .cs, downstream deps · Proceeding with Step 0...
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Load context + design doc from 110">
      Read project CLAUDE.md + design doc from task 110 + bff-extensions.md + ADR-010 + ADR-013.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Add NodeOutputs to RunContext">
      Extend `PlaybookRunContext.cs` with `IDictionary&lt;string, object?&gt; NodeOutputs { get; }` initialized to empty Dictionary&lt;string, object?&gt;(StringComparer.Ordinal). Confirm constructor + property semantics match existing immutable-vs-mutable style of the class.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Inject ITemplateEngine into PlaybookOrchestrationService">
      Add `ITemplateEngine` as a constructor parameter; assign to readonly field. Verify DI: `ITemplateEngine` is already registered in `AnalysisServicesModule` (or wherever — check first). If not registered for orchestrator's lifetime scope, register appropriately.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Rewrite ApplyConfigJsonTemplates">
      Replace literal `Replace` loop at line ~1921 with `ITemplateEngine.Render(node.ConfigJson, mergedContext)`. `mergedContext` = Parameters dict + NodeOutputs dict (Parameters wins on key collision per existing semantics). Preserve early-exit for `!ConfigJson.Contains("{{")`. Update node clone to use rendered configJson.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Register node output in ExecuteNodeAsync loop">
      After each node executor returns NodeOutput, if `node.OutputVariable` is non-empty: call `TemplateEngine.ConvertJsonElement(output.StructuredData)` if StructuredData is set, else use `output.TextContent`, else skip; store in `runContext.NodeOutputs[node.OutputVariable]`. Concurrency note: write site is single-threaded per playbook run.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Write xUnit tests">
      Add `PlaybookOrchestrationService_TemplateResolutionTests.cs`. Test cases:
      (a) `{{paramName}}` substitution still works (regression);
      (b) `{{nodeA.field}}` resolves to nodeA's prior output;
      (c) `{{nodeA.nested.deep}}` resolves through dotted path;
      (d) `{{nonexistent}}` renders as empty (graceful, no throw);
      (e) Parameter wins on collision when both Parameters and NodeOutputs contain the same key.
      Use real ITemplateEngine; mock executor returns canned NodeOutput.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Run full BFF test suite + verify build">
      `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` + `dotnet test tests/unit/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/` — confirm new tests pass + zero regressions.
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Step 9.5 — Quality gates">
      Invoke `/code-review` on the changed files (PlaybookOrchestrationService.cs, PlaybookRunContext.cs, new test file). Invoke `/adr-check`. Address any HIGH/CRITICAL findings before commit.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Update TASK-INDEX + current-task.md">
      Mark 111 ✅; advance current-task.md to next pending task (112).
    </step>
    <step order="10" name="Commit">
      Conventional commit. State BFF placement decision in body (per CLAUDE.md §10). Do NOT push — Wave 11 batch-pushes after task 119.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>Read (orchestrator + RunContext + tests)</tool>
    <tool>Edit (PlaybookOrchestrationService.cs, PlaybookRunContext.cs)</tool>
    <tool>Write (new test file)</tool>
    <tool>Bash (dotnet build + test + git commit)</tool>
    <tool>Skill (code-review, adr-check)</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/PlaybookOrchestrationService.cs (edited)</output>
